05286nam a22006975i 9780822376712DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223767127 a10.1515/97808223767122doi  a(DE-B1597)553866  a(OCoLC)1224278206  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE743b.B614 2014 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a327.73009/0422300aBody and Nation :bThe Global Realm of U.S. Body Politics in the Twentieth Century /cShanon Fitzpatrick, Emily S. Rosenberg. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b16 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican encounters/global interactions00tFrontmatter -- tcontents -- tintroduction -- tone Colonial Crossings -- ttwo Moral, Purposeful, and Healthful -- tthree Making Broken Bodies Whole in a Shell-Shocked World -- tfour Physical Culture's World of Bodies -- tfive "The Most Beautiful Chinese Girl in the World" -- tsix Roosevelt's Body and National Power -- tseven Making "Brown Babies" -- teight Regulating Borders and Bodies -- tnine The American Look -- tten Sammy Lee -- televen Counting the Bodies in Vietnam -- ttwelve "Nobody Wants These People" -- tepilogue When the Body Disappears -- tbibliography -- tcontributors -- tindex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBody and Nation interrogates the connections among the body, the nation, and the world in twentieth-century U.S. history. The idea that bodies and bodily characteristics are heavily freighted with values that are often linked to political and social spheres remains underdeveloped in the histories of America's relations with the rest of the world. Attentive to diverse state and nonstate actors, the contributors provide historically grounded insights into the transnational dimensions of biopolitics. Their subjects range from the regulation of prostitution in the Philippines by the U.S. Army to Cold War ideals of American feminine beauty, and from "body counts" as metrics of military success to cultural representations of Mexican migrants in the United States as public health threats. By considering bodies as complex, fluctuating, and interrelated sites of meaning, the contributors to this collection offer new insights into the workings of both soft and hard power.Contributors. Frank Costigliola, Janet M. Davis, Shanon Fitzpatrick, Paul A. Kramer, Shirley Jennifer Lim, Mary Ting Yi Lui, Natalia Molina, Brenda Gayle Plummer, Emily S. Rosenberg, Kristina Shull, Annessa C. Stagner, Marilyn B. Young  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aHuman bodyxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aStagner, Annessa C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlummer, Brenda Gayle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenberg, Emily S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzpatrick, Shanon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCostigliola, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Janet M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShull, Kristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoung, Marilyn B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLui, Mary Ting Yi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMolina, Natalia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKramer, Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenberg, Emily S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 